      <h1 class="font-headline text-3xl md:text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tighter text-on-surface mb-4">
        {post.title}
      </h1>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Corrugated cardboard sheets are one of the most versatile packaging materials in Malaysia. Beyond making boxes, they serve 10+ critical functions in protecting products, organizing shipments, and supporting safe logistics.
      </p>
    </div>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">
        Why Corrugated Cardboard Sheets Matter to Your Packaging Strategy
      </h2>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Many packaging managers view corrugated cardboard sheets as a secondary material, useful only for making boxes. This underestimates their value. In reality, corrugated sheets are force multipliers for packaging efficiency—they extend the life of your carton boxes, provide additional protection at minimal cost, and solve problems that boxes alone cannot address.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The honeycomb structure of corrugated cardboard—alternating layers of flat and fluted paper—creates exceptional strength-to-weight ratio. This makes it ideal for cushioning, reinforcing, and organizing items within boxes and on pallets. A single sheet costs just RM 0.80-3.00 depending on size and wall thickness, making it one of the most cost-effective protective materials available in Malaysia.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        By understanding the 10 primary uses of corrugated sheets, Malaysian businesses can reduce damage rates, optimize box sizing, minimize excess void fill materials, and ultimately reduce overall packaging costs.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">
        10 Practical Uses of Corrugated Cardboard Sheets
      </h2>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        1. Product Dividers and Compartments
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Create custom compartments within boxes by cutting and folding corrugated sheets. Perfect for separating fragile items, organizing multiple SKUs, or creating individual slots for products like glassware, electronics, or cosmetics. This prevents items from touching and damaging each other during transit.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        2. Packing Layers and Stacking Separators
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Layer corrugated sheets between stacked items to distribute weight evenly and prevent crushing. Particularly useful for packaging like cookies, crackers, ceramics, and flat items. A layer between every 3-5 items dramatically reduces breakage.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        3. Void Fill and Gap Padding
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Crumple or cut corrugated sheets to fill empty spaces in boxes. This prevents item movement during transit at a fraction of the cost of bubble wrap or foam peanuts. One sheet can fill multiple box gaps.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        4. Protective Wrapping for Fragile Items
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Wrap dishes, glasses, artwork, or electronics in 2-3 layers of corrugated sheets for impact protection. The corrugation absorbs shock better than flat cardboard or paper alone. This method is standard in moving companies and luxury goods shipping.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        5. Pallet Separators and Slip Sheets
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Place corrugated sheets between pallet layers to create stable stacking, prevent moisture wicking, and allow forklift access without pallets. Essential for warehouse operations and long-distance logistics.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        6. Corner and Edge Protection
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Cut corrugated sheets into corner pieces and edge protectors for furniture, paintings, mirrors, and electronics. Reinforce shipping boxes at corners where they're most likely to absorb impact during handling.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        7. Frame and Rig Building
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Create custom frames, support structures, and shipping rigs using corrugated sheets. Businesses assembling furniture or oversized items often use corrugated rigging to maintain product shape and prevent damage.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        8. Furniture and Upholstery Padding
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Use corrugated sheets as protective layers when shipping sofas, chairs, tables, and upholstered items. Stack multiple sheets around furniture to absorb impacts that occur during moving and handling.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        9. Electronics and Appliance Shielding
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Build custom protective cases for TVs, monitors, computers, refrigerators, and washers using corrugated sheets. The rigidity of double-wall or triple-wall sheets provides structural support while the fluted core absorbs shocks.
      </p>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        10. Floor Protection During Moves and Storage
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
        Layer corrugated sheets as floor protection when moving furniture or storing items in warehouses. They prevent moisture transfer from concrete floors and protect flooring from scratches and moisture damage.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">
        Understanding Corrugated Sheet Types and Strength
      </h2>

      <div class="bg-surface-variant/50 border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-2xl p-6 my-8">
        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-0 mb-4">
          Corrugated Sheet Specifications
        </h3>
        <table class="w-full font-body text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/20">
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-2 font-bold">Type</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-2 font-bold">Structure</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-2 font-bold">Strength</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-2 font-bold">Best For</th>
              <th class="text-left py-3 px-2 font-bold">Price</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/20">
              <td class="py-3 px-2 font-bold">Single-Wall</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">One fluted layer</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">Standard</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">Light items, void fill, wrapping</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">RM 0.80-1.20</td>
            </tr>
            <tr class="border-b border-outline-variant/20">
              <td class="py-3 px-2 font-bold">Double-Wall</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">Two fluted layers</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">Heavy-duty</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">Fragile items, padding, protection</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">RM 1.50-2.50</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td class="py-3 px-2 font-bold">Triple-Wall</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">Three fluted layers</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">Maximum</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">High-value items, delicate electronics</td>
              <td class="py-3 px-2">RM 2.50-3.50</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-6 mb-3">
        Choosing the Right Sheet Type
      </h3>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-3">
        <strong>Single-wall sheets</strong> are cost-effective for lightweight applications where minimal protection is needed. Use for void fill, basic padding, and non-critical packaging.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-3">
        <strong>Double-wall sheets</strong> are the sweet spot for most e-commerce and logistics applications. They provide substantial protection while remaining cost-effective. Perfect for fragile items, padding, and protective dividers.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        <strong>Triple-wall sheets</strong> are reserved for high-value items, sensitive electronics, and applications where maximum protection justifies the higher cost.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">
        Cost Savings Through Smart Sheet Usage
      </h2>

      <div class="bg-surface-variant/50 border border-outline-variant/20 rounded-2xl p-6 my-8">
        <h3 class="font-headline text-xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-0 mb-4">
          Example: Packaging 100 Units of Fragile Items
        </h3>
        <ul class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4 space-y-2 list-none">
          <li><strong>Using only bubble wrap:</strong> 100 units × RM 0.50 = RM 50</li>
          <li><strong>Using corrugated sheets + minimal bubble wrap:</strong> (100 sheets ÷ 3 = 34 sheets needed)</li>
          <li className="ml-4">34 sheets × RM 1.00 + 50% bubble wrap = RM 34 + RM 25 = RM 59</li>
        </ul>
        <hr class="border-outline-variant/20 my-4" />
        <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-4">
          While this example shows similar costs, corrugated sheets actually provide better protection and can be reused in your warehouse, making them superior economically and functionally.
        </p>
        <p class="font-body text-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed mb-0">
          More importantly, using corrugated sheets reduces damage rates by 15-25% compared to bubble wrap alone, directly improving your profit margins through fewer returns and replacements.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="font-headline text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-on-surface mt-10 mb-4">
